    "body": "# Add per-class weight support to cross entropy kernel\r\n\r\n## Summary\r\n\r\nThis PR adds optional per-class `weight` support to the fused cross entropy forward and backward kernels, matching the semantics of `torch.nn.functional.cross_entropy(weight=...)`.\r\n\r\nWhen a weight tensor is provided, the per-sample loss becomes `w[target] * CE(x, target)` and the gradient becomes `w[target] * (softmax(x) - one_hot(target))`. The weight parameter is fully optional. When `weight=None`, the kernel compiles to a separate binary via `@jit_cache` with no overhead.\r\n\r\n## Noteworthy Changes that may impact previous versions\r\n\r\n- `CrossEntropyFunction`: saves weight on ctx, passes to backward; added `.contiguous()` on dloss to fix pre-existing stride-0 crash with scalar upstream gradients\r\n- Weighted mean reduction: `loss.sum() / (weight[target.clamp(min=0)] * valid).sum()` in the case weight is included.\r\n\r\n## Correctness\r\n\r\nAdded `tests/test_cross_entropy_weight.py` including weighted CE tests.\r\n\r\nAll tests pass compare against `torch.nn.functional.cross_entropy(weight=...)` as reference using atol=5e-5, rtol=1e-5.\r\n\r\n## Throughput (B200, bf16)\r\n\r\nThe `weight=None` path compiles to a separate kernel (`has_weights=False`), so there is zero overhead for unweighted CE:\r\n\r\n| Problem Size | main branch | feat (no weight) | delta |\r\n|---|---|---|---|\r\n| 4096×4096 fwd | 0.0180 ms | 0.0180 ms | 0.0% |\r\n| 4096×65536 fwd | 0.1281 ms | 0.1280 ms | -0.1% |\r\n| 8192×128256 fwd | 0.5486 ms | 0.5500 ms | +0.3% |\r\n| 32768×65536 fwd | 0.9546 ms | 0.9606 ms | +0.6% |\r\n| 4096×65536 bwd | 0.1967 ms | 0.1782 ms | -9.4% |\r\n| 8192×128256 bwd | 0.8044 ms | 0.7181 ms | -10.7% |\r\n| 32768×65536 bwd | 1.5032 ms | 1.3975 ms | -7.0% |\r\n\r\nForward: within noise (±0.6%). Backward: actually ~7-12% faster due to kernel restructuring.\r\n\r\n### Weighted path overhead vs unweighted\r\n\r\nThis measures the cost of the extra `weight[target]` global memory load by comparing quack with weight vs quack without weight (both on the feat branch). This is not a comparison against main (see above for that).\r\n\r\n| Problem Size | quack (no weight) | quack (weighted) | Weight cost | vs PyTorch weighted |\r\n|---|---|---|---|---|\r\n| 4096×32768 fwd | 0.068 ms | 0.075 ms | +9.5% | **3.3x faster** |\r\n| 4096×128256 fwd | 0.277 ms | 0.297 ms | +7.2% | **4.5x faster** |\r\n| 8192×65536 fwd | 0.245 ms | 0.264 ms | +8.0% | **4.4x faster** |\r\n| 8192×128256 fwd | 0.550 ms | 0.580 ms | +5.4% | **4.6x faster** |\r\n| 32768×65536 fwd | 0.961 ms | 1.012 ms | +5.4% | **4.7x faster** |\r\n| 4096×32768 bwd | 0.095 ms | 0.102 ms | +7.3% | **4.3x faster** |\r\n| 4096×128256 bwd | 0.354 ms | 0.376 ms | +6.1% | **4.7x faster** |\r\n| 8192×128256 bwd | 0.718 ms | 0.753 ms | +4.9% | **4.7x faster** |\r\n| 32768×65536 bwd | 1.398 ms | 1.507 ms | +7.8% | **4.7x faster** |\r\n\r\nWeight adds 5-10% overhead (one extra global memory load of `weight[target]` per sample), while still remaining 3-4x faster than PyTorch's native `F.cross_entropy(weight=...)`.\r\n\r\n\r\n<img width=\"2384\" height=\"1476\" alt=\"benchmark_results\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a932a9e9-6d3f-42f7-af71-209ba1988a26\" />\r\n",
